The user is asking how to make connections in the node editor. They're probably having trouble connecting nodes - clicking an output port and then clicking an input port to create a connection.

Let me think about how the connection logic works in the code:

1. Click on an output port (filled circle on the right side of a node) - this starts the connection
2. A dashed line follows your mouse
3. Click on an input port (hollow circle on the left side of a different node) - this completes the connection

The issue might be:
1. They're clicking input ports first (won't work - must start from output)
2. They're clicking on the same node (won't work - can't connect to self)
3. The click targets might be too small
4. Something else in the UI is intercepting clicks

Let me explain the process clearly and check if there's a bug in the logic.

Looking at the code:

```javascript
const handlePortClick = (e, nodeId, portId, isOutput) => {
  e.stopPropagation();
  const pos = getPortPosition(nodeId, portId, isOutput);

  if (!connecting) {
    if (isOutput) {  // Only start connection from output ports
      setConnecting({
        fromNode: nodeId,
        fromPort: portId,
        startX: pos.x,
        startY: pos.y,
        currentX: pos.x,
        currentY: pos.y
      });
    }
  } else {
    if (!isOutput && connecting.fromNode !== nodeId) {  // Complete on input port of different node
      const newConnection = {
        id: `c${Date.now()}`,
        from: connecting.fromNode,
        fromPort: connecting.fromPort,
        to: nodeId,
        toPort: portId,
        type: 'custom'
      };
      setConnections(prev => [...prev, newConnection]);
    }
    setConnecting(null);
  }
};
```

The connection mechanism follows a precise two-step interaction. First, users must click an output port to initiate the connection, which triggers a visual dashed line. Then, they select an input port on a different node to complete the link. The code ensures connections can only be made between different nodes and from output to input ports.Ah, lemme explain the flow:

